Dataline Analytics Competition¶

Context:¶

The Tanzanian tourism sector plays a significant role in the Tanzanian economy, contributing 17% to the country's GDP and 25% of all foreign exchange revenues. The sector, which provides direct employment for more than 600,000 people and up to 2 million people indirectly, generted approximately $2.4 billion in 2018 according to government statistics. Tanzania received a record 1.1 million international visitor arrivals in 2014, mostly from Europe, the US and Africa. Tanzania is the only country in the world which has allocated more than 25% of it's total area of wildlife, national parks and protected areas. There are 16 national parks in Tanzania, 28 game reserves, 44 game-controlled areas, two marine parks and one conservation area.

Objective:¶

The objective of this competition is to explore and build a linear regression model that will predict the spending behaviour of tourists visiting Tanzania. The model can be used by different tour operators and the Tanzania Tourism Board to automatically help tourists across the world estimate their expenditure before visiting Tanzania.

Data Description¶

The dataset describes 6476 rows of up-to-date information on tourist expenditure collected by the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) in Tanzania. The dataset was collected to gain a better understanding of the status of the tourism sector and provide an instrument that will enable sector growth. The survey covers seven departure points, namely: Julius Nyerere International Airport, Kilimanjaro International Airport, Abeid Amani Karume International Airport, and the Namanga, Tunduma, Mtukula and Manyovu border points.

    • Twenty-three Columns

        df_train_tmp[label] = content.astype("category").cat.as_ordered()

total_male
In [119]:
# Fill numeric rows with median
for label, content in df_train_tmp.items():
    if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(content):
        if pd.isnull(content).sum():
            # Add a binary column which tells us if the data was missing or not
            df_train_tmp[label+"_is_missing"] = pd.isnull(content)
            # Fill missing numeric values with mode
            df_train_tmp[label] = content.fillna(content.mode())

Why add a binary column indicating whether the data was missing or not?

We can easily fill all of the missing numeric values in our dataset. However, a numeric value may be missing for a reason. In other words, absence of evidence may be evidence of absence. Adding a binary column which indicates whether the value was missing or not helps to retain this information.

# Turn categorical variables into numbers
for label, content in  df_train_tmp.items():

    if not pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(content):
        # Add binary column to inidicate whether sample had missing value

        # We add the +1 because pandas encodes missing categories as -1
        df_train_tmp[label] = pd.Categorical(content).codes+1

Evaluate Model Performance¶

In [292]:
# Create Evaluation function
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_log_error, mean_absolute_error

# Create function to evaluate our model
def show_scores(model):
    train_preds = model.predict(X_train)
    test_preds = model.predict(X_test)
    scores ={"Training MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_train, train_preds),
             "Test MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_test, test_preds),
             "Training R^2": model.score(X_train, y_train),
             "Test R^2": model.score(X_test, y_test)}
    return scores

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights

From the EDA(Exploratory data analysis) performed at the beginning of the notebook, we see profitable aspects to invest in the tourism business and customer's preferences. We can take actions and try to optimize the business using the data we've found to increase profit.

From our EDA:

  • We see that the top 5 countries with the highest spending statistic are:

    • USA
    • Italy
    • United Kingdom
    • France
    • Australia

  • Age_group 45-64 are the highest spenders

  • Spouse is the highest spenders in travel_with, USA has the most spending tourists
  • Customers spend an average of aproximately 9 nights in Tanzania_mainland.
  • Customers spend an average of approximately 2 nights in Zanzibar
  • Cash is the most preferred form of payment by tourists
  • Aspects of tourism that are more profitable and in which it is worthwhile to invest in are: Wildlife Tourism & Beach Tourism

Recommendations

Our model performed pretty poorly, the next step obviously is to try and improve it's performance via hyperparameter tuning but the model instructed to be used which is LinearRegression doesn't really have much parameters to tune.

What we can do to solve the problem is to try other machine learning models such as LogisticRegression and RandomForestRegressor, these models will perform better on our dataset and can be tuned manually and also by using GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV.
